There is undocumented member `DeviceNode` in `DEVOBJ_EXTENSION` because it is not a part of WDM.h and NTDDK.h, so private to the IO or PnP Managers. In any case it is NULL for non-PDO's so "unsupported way" is 

```
if (DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->DeviceNode) {
        // PDO!
    } else {
        // non-PDO!
    }

```

I'd prefer not to use it. Instead of it, you can find actual device object via `IoGetDeviceObjectPointer` or by walking through devobj list starting from `PDRIVER_OBJECT`.
In order to determinate whether devobj is PDO send QDR/TargetDeviceRelation (unref `PDEVICE_OBJECT` in list when done). If succeeded, resulting devobj in the QDR will be the PDO your device. [Here is](http://blogs.msdn.com/b/doronh/archive/2006/06/12/629120.aspx) a good explanation of this. Another option is to use `DO_BUS_ENUMERATED_DEVICE`.
Also take into account that this flag does not means *initialized* PDO. It set before initialization and upon structure allocation.

After hours of investigating the problem, I figured out a solution. I added an `ng-change` directive to my radio input that would call a function in the controller to set the other radio button's value to false.

In the controller (note that I am using the `each` method in Underscore.js, but you can similarly iterate using a standard for loop):

```
$scope.setTrueFalseRadioState = function (answer) {
  _.each(question.answers, function (a) {
    if (a.choice !== answer.choice) {
      a.is_correct = false;
    }
  });
};

```

And I added the `ng-change` attribute to the input tag:

```
<input type="radio" name="true_false_choice" ng-model="answer.is_correct"
       ng-value="true" ng-change="setTrueFalseRadioState(answer)">

```

By doing this, the user can now go back to a question that was created earlier and edit the question (by changing the correct answer from True to False or vice versa), and the `is_correct` property will be updated appropriately based on the state of the radio button.

